1

00:00:00,000  -->  00:00:03,220
We have implemented a particular architecture for

2

00:00:03,220  -->  00:00:07,250
large language models called decoder-only architecture.

3

00:00:07,250  -->  00:00:10,480
It turns out that there are other architectures,

4

00:00:10,480  -->  00:00:15,540
and now we'll briefly cover what they are and how they differ from each other.

5

00:00:15,540  -->  00:00:19,195
Transformers were initially introduced in a paper called,

6

00:00:19,195  -->  00:00:21,145
Attention is All You Need.

7

00:00:21,145  -->  00:00:24,640
This paper described an architecture that is

8

00:00:24,640  -->  00:00:28,360
more complex comparing to the architecture that we've implemented.

9

00:00:28,360  -->  00:00:32,460
You see the image of this architecture on the screen right now.

10

00:00:32,460  -->  00:00:35,760
It also was created for a different purpose.

11

00:00:35,760  -->  00:00:38,580
Instead of having a goal to generate text,

12

00:00:38,580  -->  00:00:42,040
the authors of the paper were working on a new way

13

00:00:42,040  -->  00:00:46,740
of translating text from one language to the other.

14

00:00:47,420  -->  00:00:51,020
But if you look closely at this diagram,

15

00:00:51,020  -->  00:00:55,650
you will see that the right part should be somewhat familiar.

16

00:00:55,650  -->  00:00:58,180
It has the embedding layer,

17

00:00:58,180  -->  00:01:00,395
the positional encoding,

18

00:01:00,395  -->  00:01:03,260
the masked multi-head attention,

19

00:01:03,260  -->  00:01:05,160
and just to remind you,

20

00:01:05,160  -->  00:01:11,695
masked is referred to a triangular mask we've used to change the attention scores.

21

00:01:11,695  -->  00:01:16,920
It also has the feed-forward layer with the residual connection,

22

00:01:16,920  -->  00:01:22,340
and the Nx means that this block is repeated multiple times,

23

00:01:22,340  -->  00:01:25,200
similar to how we had it in our model.

24

00:01:25,200  -->  00:01:29,220
What we did not have in our model was this section on the left,

25

00:01:29,220  -->  00:01:35,070
called encoder, and we also didn't have the connection between these blocks.

26

00:01:35,070  -->  00:01:38,840
The encoder block on the left was used to

27

00:01:38,840  -->  00:01:43,300
encode information about an input text for translation.

28

00:01:43,300  -->  00:01:47,840
The part on the right that we've implemented is called a decoder.

29

00:01:47,840  -->  00:01:52,300
It receives a part of the translation it has generated so far,

30

00:01:52,300  -->  00:01:57,260
and given the encoded inputs it generates the next token.

31

00:01:57,260  -->  00:02:02,730
The encoder is very similar to a decoder with the main difference

32

00:02:02,730  -->  00:02:08,570
that it uses a multi-head attention instead of a masked multi-head attention,

33

00:02:08,570  -->  00:02:11,960
meaning that it computes attention scores based on

34

00:02:11,960  -->  00:02:16,780
all tokens in the input without using the triangular mask.

35

00:02:16,780  -->  00:02:21,200
When using this model we pass two different inputs.

36

00:02:21,200  -->  00:02:23,000
Input to the encoder,

37

00:02:23,000  -->  00:02:25,430
which is a text to translate,

38

00:02:25,430  -->  00:02:30,500
and decoder's input that contains a partially translated output,

39

00:02:30,500  -->  00:02:36,975
and the decoder's input that contains a part of the translation generated so far.

40

00:02:36,975  -->  00:02:41,565
The encoder input goes through all the layers of the encoder,

41

00:02:41,565  -->  00:02:47,370
and the output from its final layer is sent to every layer of the decoder.

42

00:02:47,370  -->  00:02:50,170
Decoder layers then use this information from

43

00:02:50,170  -->  00:02:54,550
the encoder to generate the next token in the translation.

44

00:02:54,550  -->  00:02:58,190
Because the input to the encoder block does not change,

45

00:02:58,190  -->  00:03:01,070
we can compute it once and pass it to

46

00:03:01,070  -->  00:03:05,030
all decoder blocks while generating the output text.

47

00:03:05,030  -->  00:03:08,710
Let's look at an example of how an encoder-decoder model

48

00:03:08,710  -->  00:03:13,170
would translate text from English to French.

49

00:03:13,170  -->  00:03:19,290
We would first tokenize the text we want to translate and convert it into token IDs.

50

00:03:19,290  -->  00:03:22,650
Then we would pass these IDs to the encoder for

51

00:03:22,650  -->  00:03:26,790
it to build a representation of a phrase we want to translate.

52

00:03:26,790  -->  00:03:29,790
To start the translation process we would pass

53

00:03:29,790  -->  00:03:35,250
a special character called Start of the sequence, to the decoder.

54

00:03:35,250  -->  00:03:39,790
Decoder will read this input and the encoder's output,

55

00:03:39,790  -->  00:03:44,610
and will produce the first token ID of the translated phrase,

56

00:03:44,610  -->  00:03:48,050
which corresponds to the following French word.

57

00:03:48,050  -->  00:03:50,690
We would then add the generated token ID to

58

00:03:50,690  -->  00:03:54,630
the input as the decoder and send it to the decoder again.

59

00:03:54,630  -->  00:03:57,230
Decoder will now receive a new input with

60

00:03:57,230  -->  00:04:03,545
the same encoder output as on the previous step and generate the new token.

61

00:04:03,545  -->  00:04:07,270
We then repeat this process again and generate

62

00:04:07,270  -->  00:04:10,550
more and more output tokens until

63

00:04:10,550  -->  00:04:14,810
the model generates the special end of the sequence token,

64

00:04:14,810  -->  00:04:19,130
which means that the model has translated the whole phrase.

65

00:04:19,130  -->  00:04:26,620
We can then convert token IDs into the human-readable sentence that looks like this.

66

00:04:26,620  -->  00:04:30,570
Using encoders and decoders as building blocks,

67

00:04:30,570  -->  00:04:34,245
we can have three different network architectures.

68

00:04:34,245  -->  00:04:40,070
Decoder-only model that only has a decoder part and no encoder.

69

00:04:40,070  -->  00:04:43,370
This is what we've implemented in this lesson.

70

00:04:43,370  -->  00:04:47,455
This architecture is well suited for tax generation tasks,

71

00:04:47,455  -->  00:04:51,850
and is used by models like GPT and Lama.

72

00:04:51,850  -->  00:04:56,490
The other option is called encoder-decoder models.

73

00:04:56,490  -->  00:05:00,350
In this case we have both encoder and decoder blocks.

74

00:05:00,350  -->  00:05:05,250
These models are good from converting from one sequence to another.

75

00:05:05,250  -->  00:05:10,485
For example, if we need to translate text into another language.

76

00:05:10,485  -->  00:05:16,210
Some models implementing this architecture include BART and T5.

77

00:05:16,210  -->  00:05:20,400
Finally, the last option is encoder-only models.

78

00:05:20,400  -->  00:05:22,890
These models don't have a decoder,

79

00:05:22,890  -->  00:05:26,240
and only pass inputs through an encoder.

80

00:05:26,240  -->  00:05:30,240
This is useful if we want to build a representation for

81

00:05:30,240  -->  00:05:35,515
text classification like sentiment analysis or spam detection.

82

00:05:35,515  -->  00:05:40,670
BART is an example of a model using this architecture.
